            "id": "352d74b248ba4ba8b1a00",
            "questionText": "A cyclist is pedaling up a hill at a constant speed. The combined weight of the cyclist and bicycle is $!$700 N$!$. The hill has a height of $!$50 m$!$. The cyclist's power output is $!$100 W$!$, and it takes them $!$60 seconds$!$ to reach the top of the hill. Assuming their body consumes $!$5000 J$!$ of energy during that time, calculate the efficiency $!$\\eta$!$ of the cyclist's energy conversion in percentage.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "2d00587cf49e4e7f97124",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the appropriate formula to calculate the gain in gravitational potential energy when climbing a hill. Choose the formula that best relates potential energy to the vertical height climbed.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "3c01ec37-9e55-45a6-9bc8-34733b46e8e7"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$E_p = mgh$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$E_p = \\frac{1}{2} mv^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$E_p = F \\times t$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "e5beeffecd5142dea3e45",
                    "stepText": "Now, use the formula you selected to calculate the gravitational potential energy gain when the cyclist climbs a height of $!$50 m$!$ with a weight of $!$700 N$!$. Multiply the weight by the height.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "35000"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "J",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "3c01ec37-9e55-45a6-9bc8-34733b46e8e7"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "2ddb8e1fed1c407581cf9",
                    "stepText": "Great, next let\u2019s determine the relationship to compute work output from power and time. Identify the correct formula that expresses work done as a product of power and time.",
